n Post-Yugoslav Artistic Practices: Or, Art as ... / rDedić, Nikola -- tPart 3: Reconfiguring the Post-Yugoslav Present: Towards New Forms of Community and Identity -- tGarbage Heap, Storehouse, Encyclopedia: Metaphors for a Post-Yugoslav Cultural Memory / rSnel, Guido -- tSmall Town as the Scene of a Memory Encounter: Portraits and Commemorations of Radomir Konstantinović / rZorić, Vladimir -- tRecollecting an Alternative Modernity: Aleksandar Zograf's Flea Market Archaeologies / rBeronja, Vlad -- tA Public Language of Grief: Art, Poetry, and Transitional Justice in Post-Conflict Bosnia / rArsenijević, Damir / Husanović, Jasmina / Wastell, Sari -- tDigital Afterlife: Ex-Yugoslav Pop Culture Icons and Social Media / rPogačar, Martin -- tNotes on Contributors -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex of Names  aMemory in the Balkans has often been described as binding, authoritative, and non-negotiable, functioning as a banner of war. This book challenges such a one-dimensional representation and offers a more nuanced analysis that accommodates frequently ignored instances of transnational solidarity, dialogue, communal mourning and working through a difficult past. Exploring a broad range of memorial practices, the book focuses on the ways in which cultural memory is mediated, performed and critically reworked by literature and the arts in the former Yugoslavia. Against the methodological nationalism of works that study Serbian, Croatian, or Bosniak culture as self-contained, this book examines post-Yugoslav literature, film, visual culture, and politicized art practices from a supranational angle. Not solely focusing on traumatic memories, but also exploring how post-Yugoslav cultural practices mobilize memory for a politics of hope, this volume moves beyond the trauma paradigm that still dominates memory studies. In its scope and approach, the book shows the relevance of the cultural memory of Eastern European citizens and the contribution they can offer to the building of Europe's shared cultural memory and transnational identity.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aBosnian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCollective memory in literature. 0aCroatian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aMass media and culturezBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aMass media and culturezCroatia. 0aMass media and culturezSerbia. 0aPsychic trauma in literature. 0aSerbian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aYugoslav literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aCultural memory. 4aformer Yugoslavia. 4amedia. 4atrauma. 70(DE-601)1056811990(DE-588)4133301-9aSerbisch2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-588)4035964-5aLiteratur2gnd 70(DE-601)1062583890(DE-588)4033245-7aKroatisch2gnd 70(DE-601)2313508130(DE-588)4464132-1aBosnisch2gnd 70(DE-601)3251381410(DE-588)4578384-6aPsychisches TraumagMotiv2gnd 70(DE-601)3304230370(DE-588)4639552-0aKollektives GedächtnisgMotiv2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBeronja, Vlad, eeditor.1 aVervaet, Stijn, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104317800 cprintz978311043943440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110431575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110431575.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016